13 (2022 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
14 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
15 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
16 Article – Education
17 15–106.12.
18 (A) IN THIS SECTION, “STATE OR LOCAL PUBLIC SAFETY EMPLOYEE” HAS
19 THE MEANING STATED IN § 18–601 OF THIS ARTICLE.
20 (B) NOTWITHSTANDING THE STATE OR COUNTY IN WHICH THE SPOUSE OR
21 THE CHILD RESIDES, A SPOUSE OR A FINANCIALLY DEPENDENT CHILD OF A STATE
22 OR LOCAL PUBLIC SAFETY EMPLOYEE WHO DIES AS A RESULT OF OR IN THE COURSE
23 OF PERFORMANCE OF DUTIES IS EXEMPT FROM PAYING OUT–OF–STATE OR
24 OUT–OF–COUNTY TUITION AT A PUBLIC INSTITUTION OF HIGHER EDUCATION IN THE
25 STATE.
26 (C) THE COMMISSION SHALL ADOPT REGULATIONS TO IMPLEMENT THIS
27 SECTION.
28 18–601.
29 (a) (1) In this section the following words have the meanings indicated.
30 (5) “State or local public safety employee” means a person who is employed
31 in the State as:
32 (i) A career or volunteer member of a:

HOUSE BILL 3 3
1 1. Fire department;
2 2. Ambulance company or squad; or
3 3. Rescue company or squad;
4 (ii) A law enforcement officer;
5 (iii) A correctional officer; or
6 (iv) A member of the Maryland National Guard who was a resident
7 of this State at the time of death.
8 (a) (1) In this section the following words have the meanings indicated.
9 (2) “Disabled public safety employee” means a State or local public safety
10 employee who sustains an injury in the line of duty that:
11 (i) Precludes the individual from continuing to serve or be employed
12 as a State or local public safety employee; and
13 (ii) In the case of a volunteer member of a fire department or
14 ambulance or rescue company or squad, precludes the member from continuing to be
15 employed in the nonpublic safety occupation in which the member is engaged at the time of
16 the injury.
17 (3) “Fund” means the Edward T. Conroy and Jean B. Cryor Scholarship
18 Fund.
19 (4) “School employee” includes an employee of a public or nonpublic school
20 in the State.
21 (5) “State or local public safety employee” means a person who is employed
22 in the State as:
23 (i) A career or volunteer member of a:
24 1. Fire department;
25 2. Ambulance company or squad; or
26 3. Rescue company or squad;
27 (ii) A law enforcement officer;
28 (iii) A correctional officer; or

4 HOUSE BILL 3
1 (iv) A member of the Maryland National Guard who was a resident
2 of this State at the time of death.
3 (6) “Surviving spouse” means a person who has not remarried.
4 (7) “Victim of the September 11, 2001, terrorist attacks” means a Maryland
5 resident who was killed as a result of the attacks on the World Trade Center in New York
6 City, the attack on the Pentagon in Virginia, or the crash of United Airlines Flight 93 in
7 Pennsylvania.
8 (b) There is a program of scholarships that are awarded by eligible postsecondary
9 institutions under this section.
10 (c) (1) The program for uniformed services and public safety personnel and
11 their eligible dependents is the Edward T. and Mary A. Conroy Memorial Scholarship
12 Program.
13 (2) The program for eligible dependents of public and nonpublic school
14 employees is the Jean B. Cryor Memorial Scholarship Program.
15 (d) (1) A person may apply to an eligible postsecondary institution for a
16 scholarship under this section if the person:
17 (i) 1. Is accepted for admission or enrolled in the regular
18 undergraduate, graduate or professional program at an eligible institution;
19 2. Is enrolled in a 2–year terminal certificate program in
20 which the course work is acceptable for transfer credit for an accredited baccalaureate
21 program in an eligible institution; or
22 3. Is enrolled in a private career school;
23 (ii) Is at least 16 years old; and
24 (iii) Meets the other eligibility criteria specified in this section.
25 (2) To apply for a scholarship under this section, the following persons are
26 required to be a resident of Maryland at the time of application or at the time of the disabling
27 or fatal event:
28 (i) A son, daughter, stepson, stepdaughter, or the surviving spouse of
29 a member of the uniformed services who:
30 1. Died as a result of service after December 7, 1941;
31 2. Suffered a service connected 100% permanent disability
32 after December 7, 1941; or

HOUSE BILL 3 5
1 3. Was declared to be a prisoner of war or missing in action,
2 if that occurred on or after January 1, 1960, as a result of the Vietnam conflict, and if the
3 child was born prior to or while the parent was a prisoner of war or missing in action;
4 (ii) A prisoner of war or missing in action, if that occurred on or after
5 January 1, 1960, as a result of the Vietnam conflict and was a resident of this State at the
6 time the person was declared to be a prisoner of war or missing in action;
7 (iii) A veteran who:
8 1. Suffers a service connected disability of 25% or greater; and
9 2. Has exhausted or is no longer eligible for federal veterans’
10 educational benefits;
11 (iv) A son, daughter, stepson, or stepdaughter of or the surviving
12 spouse of a victim of the September 11, 2001, terrorist attacks;
13 (v) A son, daughter, stepson, or stepdaughter of a school employee
14 who, as a result of an act of violence:
15 1. Died in the line of duty; or
16 2. Sustained an injury in the line of duty that rendered the
17 school employee 100% disabled; or
18 (vi) The surviving spouse of a school employee who, as a result of an
19 act of violence:
20 1. Died in the line of duty; or
21 2. Sustained an injury in the line of duty that rendered the
22 school employee 100% disabled.
23 (3) To apply for a scholarship under this section, the following persons are
24 not required to be a resident of Maryland at the time of application or at the time of the
25 disabling or fatal event:
26 (i) 1. A son, daughter, stepson, or stepdaughter of any State or
27 local public safety employee killed in the line of duty; or
28 2. The surviving spouse of any State or local public safety
29 employee killed in the line of duty; or
30 (ii) 1. A disabled public safety employee;

6 HOUSE BILL 3
1 2. A son, daughter, stepson, or stepdaughter of a disabled
2 public safety employee who sustains an injury in the line of duty that renders the public
3 safety employee 100% disabled; or
4 3. The surviving spouse of a disabled public safety employee
5 who sustains an injury in the line of duty that renders the public safety employee 100%
6 disabled.
7 (e) A scholarship awarded under this section:
8 (1) May be used for the tuition and mandatory fees at any eligible
9 institution; and
10 (2) May not:
11 (i) Exceed the equivalent annual tuition and mandatory fees of a
12 resident undergraduate student at the 4–year public institution of higher education within
13 the University System of Maryland, other than the University of Maryland Global Campus
14 and University of Maryland, Baltimore Campus, with the highest annual expenses for a
15 full–time resident undergraduate; and
16 (ii) Be less than the lesser of:
17 1. $3,000; or
18 2. The equivalent annual tuition and mandatory fees of a
19 resident of the institution attended by the recipient of the scholarship.
20 (f) (1) Each postsecondary institution shall determine the eligibility of persons
21 who apply to the institution for the Edward T. and Mary A. Conroy Memorial Scholarship
22 Program and the Jean B. Cryor Memorial Scholarship Program.
23 (2) Funds for the Edward T. and Mary A. Conroy Memorial Scholarship
24 Program and the Jean B. Cryor Memorial Scholarship Program shall be allocated by the
25 Commission to each postsecondary institution based on [the number of eligible recipients
26 attending each institution] A FORMULA DETERMINED BY THE COMMISSION, WHICH MAY
27 INCLUDE PRIOR YEAR ENROLLMENT, ELIGIBLE RECIPIENTS, AND INSTITUTIONAL
28 TUITION AND FEES.
29 (3) In October and February of each year, each postsecondary institution
30 shall report to the Commission the number of eligible recipients attending the institution.
31 (4) (I) The Commission shall allocate funds for awards to postsecondary
32 institutions [upon verification of eligible recipients attending the institutions] SUBJECT TO
33 THE AVAILABILITY OF FUNDS AS PROVIDED IN THE STATE BUDGET.

HOUSE BILL 3 7
1 (II) EACH POSTSECONDARY INSTITUTION MAY MAKE AWARDS
2 TO ELIGIBLE STUDENTS SUBJECT TO THE ALLOCATION OF FUNDS FROM THE
3 COMMISSION UNDER SUBPARAGRAPH (I) OF THIS PARAGRAPH.
4 (5) [If funds cannot be allocated in the fiscal year in which awards are
5 made, priority shall be given to allocating funds for those awards in the following fiscal
6 year] THE COMMISSION SHALL ADOPT GUIDELINES TO IMPLEMENT THIS
7 SUBSECTION.
8 (g) (1) Each recipient of a scholarship under this section may hold the award
9 for 5 years of full–time study or 8 years of part–time study.
10 (2) The number of eligible recipients under subsection (d)(2)(iii) of this
11 section shall be limited to 15 each year.
12 (3) An award provided under subsection (d)(2)(iv) of this section may not
13 exceed the amount specified in subsection (e)(2) of this section when combined with any other
14 scholarship received by a student based on the student’s status as a child or spouse of a
15 victim of the September 11, 2001, terrorist attacks.
16 (4) SUBJECT TO A RECIPIENT’S CONTINUED ELIGIBILITY UNDER
17 SUBSECTION (D) OF THIS SECTION AND THE AVAILABILITY OF FUNDS UNDER
18 SUBSECTION (F) OF THIS SECTION, AN AWARDING AUTHORITY SHALL GIVE PRIORITY
19 TO A RECIPIENT OF A SCHOLARSHIP BEFORE AWARDING FUNDS TO NEW APPLICANTS.
20 (h) (1) There is an Edward T. Conroy and Jean B. Cryor Scholarship Fund.
21 (2) The Commission shall administer the Fund.
22 (3) The Fund is a special, nonlapsing fund that is not subject to § 7–302 of
23 the State Finance and Procurement Article.
24 (4) The State Treasurer shall hold the Fund and the Comptroller shall
25 account for the Fund.
26 (5) The Commission:
27 (i) May accept any gift or grant from any person for the Fund;
28 (ii) Shall use any gift or grant that it receives for a scholarship from
29 the programs; and
30 (iii) Shall deposit any gift or grant that it receives for the programs
31 with the State Treasurer.

8 HOUSE BILL 3
1 (i) For fiscal year 2024 and each fiscal year thereafter, the Governor shall include
2 in the annual budget bill an appropriation of at least $4,000,000 to the Fund.
3 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
4 1, 2026.
Approved:
